                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d774">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.4061 Motion Pictures/348: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-03-18T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >March 18, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>355. Hays Organization has advised the Department of the receipt of a report that
                    the Exchange Commission<note n="5" xml:id="d774fn5">Presumably the Chinese
                        Foreign Exchange and Assets Control Commission.</note> proposes to reduce
                    the total remittances by American film companies to 2500 U. S. dollars monthly
                    from the present total of approximately 50,000 U. S. dollars. Refer your no.
                    1982 of January 3, 1944. The organization states that this is a prohibitive
                    figure which if accepted would force the American companies to operate in China
                    at a financial loss. It would be appreciated if you would investigate this
                    matter with a view to assisting the American companies and report by telegraph
                    to the Department concerning it.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
